snippet.title: John Williams & Vienna Philharmonic feat. Anne-Sophie Mutter – “Hedwig’s Theme” From “Harry Potter”
snippet.description:
John Williams & Vienna Philharmonic feat. Anne-Sophie Mutter – “Hedwig’s Theme” From “Harry Potter”
Listen to “John Williams in Vienna”: https://DG.lnk.to/DGWilliams
Subscribe here for more classical video clips – The Best Of Classical Music: http://bit.ly/Subscribe_DG

Hollywood legend John Williams conducted the world-famous Vienna Philharmonic for the very first time in a landmark concert of his best-loved movie music in January 2020. Nominated for 52 Oscars, Williams has composed the soundtracks of our lives with his scores for “Jaws”, “Star Wars”, “Indiana Jones”, “Jurassic Park” and many more. For the concert held at Vienna’s Musikverein Williams is joined by violinist Anne-Sophie Mutter for a series of the virtuosic adaptations written specially for her, including “Hedwig's Theme” From “Harry Potter”, continuing an artistic partnership formed last year for Deutsche Grammophon’s album “Across The  Stars”. The live recording is available now. Also available in Dolby Atmos®.

snippet.title: Theme (From "Sabrina" / Audio)
snippet.description:
In the midst of his work on Star Wars’ Final Episode IX John Williams has created and conducted a complete album with Anne-Sophie Mutter and in mutual admiration. It presents his personal selection of iconic themes as well as rediscovered gems from more than 40 years of his music for film. Recorded at the iconic Sony Pictures scoring stage in Los Angeles where many of the great film scores were recorded, including those of The Wizard of Oz, Gone with the Wind, Lawrence of Arabia, An American in Paris, E.T. and Schindler’s List, among many, many others. “That’s the wonderful thing about John’s music – it exists even without the film.” – Anne-Sophie Mutter

Hollywood legend John Williams has just added to an already incredibly long list of achievements by making his conducting debut with the Wiener Philharmoniker to perform iconic themes from “Jurassic Park”, “Star Wars” and “Harry Potter”, among other cinematic landmarks. The concert held at Vienna’s Musikverein in January 2020 – which was also the first performance Williams had ever conducted in continental Europe – is available now. snippet.title: Anne-Sophie Mutter & John Williams – 'Nice To Be Around' from Cinderella Liberty
snippet.description:
Anne-Sophie Mutter & John Williams – 'Nice To Be Around' from Cinderella Liberty
Discover “John Williams in Vienna”: http://dg.lnk.to/Williams 
Watch the full concert on DG Stage on July 10: https://www.umgt.de/stage_williams_YT

Under the direction of legendary film composer John Williams himself, violinist Anne-Sophie Mutter and the Boston Pops Orchestra perform a stunning new adaptation of Williams’ “Nice To Be Around” from the jazz-inflected “Cinderella Liberty” score at the Tanglewood Music Festival 2019. Williams’ remarkable ability to recast his famous music in creative new forms is on display in this new version of “Nice To Be Around”, a work chosen for their recent collaboration “Across the Stars”, where Mutter’s bluesy opening is transformed into something hopeful.

snippet.title: John Williams & Vienna Philharmonic – Williams: Imperial March (from “Star Wars”)
snippet.description:
John Williams & Vienna Philharmonic – Williams: Imperial March (from “Star Wars”)
Discover “John Williams in Vienna”: http://dg.lnk.to/Williams 

John Williams’ movie soundtracks are among the best-loved of all time. Before a single note had been played at the Hollywood legend’s debut concert with the Vienna Philharmonic, Maestro Williams received a standing ovation. Their sensational performance of the “Imperial March” from “Star Wars” underlined the rapport and affection between orchestra and composer. “It was honestly one of the best presentations of that March I’ve ever heard”, Williams reflected afterwards. “They played it as though they owned it.” 

Deutsche Grammophon releases Williams’ historic Vienna Philharmonic debut concert in audio and video formats. 'John Williams in Vienna' is now available! Also available in Dolby Atmos®.

snippet.title: John Williams & Vienna Philharmonic – “The Rebellion Is Reborn” from “Star Wars: The Last Jedi”
snippet.description:
John Williams & Vienna Philharmonic – “The Rebellion Is Reborn” from “Star Wars: The Last Jedi”
Listen to “John Williams in Vienna”: https://DG.lnk.to/Williams
Subscribe here for more classical video clips – The Best Of Classical Music: http://bit.ly/Subscribe_DG

“May the Force be with you”: thus the famous greeting and wish from Star Wars. It has a much deeper meaning than the standard “Good luck”, for luck is not enough: skill and craftsmanship are also needed,  as is the ability to employ both of them correctly and successfully. John  Williams already had this kind of “Force” when he published his first piano sonata as an unknown 19-year-old. “The Force” has been with him ever since.
 
The legendary American composer John Williams’ stature in the industry was consolidated by Jaws (1975) and Star Wars (1977). His movie soundtracks have earned countless prestigious awards, including five Oscars, five Emmys, four Golden Globes and twenty-five Grammys. As he thanked the audience at Vienna’s Musikverein for their welcome, however, he told them that the invitation to work with the Wiener Philharmoniker was “one of the greatest honours of my life”. 

Deutsche Grammophon released Williams’ historic Vienna Philharmonic debut concert in audio and video formats. Also available in Dolby Atmos®.
